AUDIENCE: What are the
challenges of effectively using

00:21:58.500 --> 00:22:00.010
spatial audio in VR?

00:22:02.912 --> 00:22:04.870
KARSH KALE: Well, I think
that that's something

00:22:04.870 --> 00:22:06.490
that we're still exploring.

00:22:06.490 --> 00:22:08.800
So I think that I'll have
to answer that question

00:22:08.800 --> 00:22:12.490
in maybe a few months, in terms
of what the challenges might

00:22:12.490 --> 00:22:13.410
be.

00:22:13.410 --> 00:22:15.124
NIRDHAR KHAZANIE: Thanks.

00:22:15.124 --> 00:22:18.440
AUDIENCE: How do you
address creative block?

00:22:18.440 --> 00:22:20.540
I think every artist
experiences that.

00:22:20.540 --> 00:22:23.450
What is your, I
guess, methodology

00:22:23.450 --> 00:22:25.190
of getting over that hump?

00:22:25.190 --> 00:22:26.900
KARSH KALE: Well,
I mean, for me,

00:22:26.900 --> 00:22:29.510
if I get a creative block when
I'm working on my own stuff,

00:22:29.510 --> 00:22:31.050
I just stop.

00:22:31.050 --> 00:22:32.470
I just stop until--

00:22:32.470 --> 00:22:35.039
I mean, for me, it doesn't
work unless I'm inspired.

00:22:35.039 --> 00:22:37.330
And sometimes I'm inspired
at 3 o'clock in the morning.

00:22:37.330 --> 00:22:38.871
I'll get straight
out of bed and I'll

00:22:38.871 --> 00:22:40.960
go start working on something.

00:22:40.960 --> 00:22:45.100
If I'm working on something for,
say, a film or something that

00:22:45.100 --> 00:22:49.120
requires a deadline, I've
amassed enough skills

00:22:49.120 --> 00:22:52.160
to be able to get it done.

00:22:52.160 --> 00:22:55.270
But I think that the
difference is getting something

00:22:55.270 --> 00:22:59.440
done that you know
will do the job,

00:22:59.440 --> 00:23:01.780
and then there's
that inspired work

00:23:01.780 --> 00:23:06.280
that you know only works
when you're inspired.

00:23:06.280 --> 00:23:08.170
AUDIENCE: You play a
lot of instruments.

00:23:08.170 --> 00:23:09.206
How did it work for you?

00:23:09.206 --> 00:23:10.830
How do you learn all
those instruments?

00:23:10.830 --> 00:23:14.070
How did you split your time
learning those instruments?

00:23:14.070 --> 00:23:17.740
Was it one instrument for
a specific period of time

00:23:17.740 --> 00:23:19.330
or how did it work?

00:23:19.330 --> 00:23:22.090
KARSH KALE: Well, I mean,
when I was growing up,

00:23:22.090 --> 00:23:23.350
I was a drummer.

00:23:23.350 --> 00:23:26.320
So whenever I had
band rehearsals,

00:23:26.320 --> 00:23:27.970
they were at my house.

00:23:27.970 --> 00:23:30.400
So all of the musicians would
bring their instruments up

00:23:30.400 --> 00:23:32.770
to my house and they
would leave them there.

00:23:32.770 --> 00:23:34.590
So I had a house full of--

00:23:34.590 --> 00:23:36.700
I had a bass and a
bass amp with pedals.

00:23:36.700 --> 00:23:38.350
I had a guitar
with guitar pedals.

00:23:38.350 --> 00:23:40.210
I had an 8-track
recorder and a keyboard.

00:23:40.210 --> 00:23:43.040
And all of this stuff that
I never played myself,

00:23:43.040 --> 00:23:44.729
but that's how I
learned how to play it.

00:23:44.729 --> 00:23:47.020
And I learned also-- because
I had an 8-track recorder,

00:23:47.020 --> 00:23:49.300
I started making my own music--

00:23:49.300 --> 00:23:50.200
terrible music.

00:23:50.200 --> 00:23:52.180
But it was my own stuff.

00:23:52.180 --> 00:23:54.340
So I was learning how
to write bass lines.

00:23:54.340 --> 00:23:56.170
And then how that
worked in counterpoint

00:23:56.170 --> 00:23:57.430
to a keyboard part.

00:23:57.430 --> 00:23:59.410
And how that worked
with a guitar part.

00:23:59.410 --> 00:24:02.110
And then how that worked
with a particular drum part

00:24:02.110 --> 00:24:03.140
that I was writing.

00:24:03.140 --> 00:24:04.960
And so these were all--

00:24:04.960 --> 00:24:09.409
that was the way for me to step
into that world of making music

00:24:09.409 --> 00:24:10.450
on different instruments.

00:24:10.450 --> 00:24:13.960
And I realized that my
fascination with music

00:24:13.960 --> 00:24:16.874
was never only based
on one instrument.

00:24:16.874 --> 00:24:18.790
When I would listen to--
when I was growing up

00:24:18.790 --> 00:24:22.210
listening to Zeppelin
or Rush or Queen,

00:24:22.210 --> 00:24:24.490
I was always listening
to really big music

00:24:24.490 --> 00:24:26.330
with a lot of stuff going on.

00:24:26.330 --> 00:24:29.720
And I always wanted to
be able to do all of it.

00:24:29.720 --> 00:24:35.690
It wasn't about being
an expert or a virtuoso

00:24:35.690 --> 00:24:38.270
at any of those
particular things.

00:24:38.270 --> 00:24:42.620
These were means to be able
to create that large sound,

00:24:42.620 --> 00:24:45.560
to be able to-- so that's why I
learned how to-- and I always--

00:24:45.560 --> 00:24:47.390
I started playing sarod
for a little while.

00:24:47.390 --> 00:24:49.440
I played santoor
for a little while.

00:24:49.440 --> 00:24:51.080
And I knew that I wasn't going
to play these instruments

00:24:51.080 --> 00:24:52.216
for the rest of my life.

00:24:52.216 --> 00:24:53.840
But there was something
that I learned.

00:24:53.840 --> 00:24:56.600
There was something that I was
able to-- that I still apply in

00:24:56.600 --> 00:24:59.650
my own music by spending
that two years playing sarod

00:24:59.650 --> 00:25:02.900
and those four years
playing santoor.

00:25:02.900 --> 00:25:06.290
As a tabla player, as a
composer, all of these things

00:25:06.290 --> 00:25:07.582
come into play.

00:25:07.582 --> 00:25:09.290
And a lot of people,
a lot of musicians--

00:25:09.290 --> 00:25:10.880
especially producers--

00:25:10.880 --> 00:25:13.370
that you meet,
oftentimes, are people

00:25:13.370 --> 00:25:15.290
who have been able
to explore a lot

00:25:15.290 --> 00:25:19.700
of different styles of music
and different instrumentation.

00:25:19.700 --> 00:25:21.890
It's important to know
the physicality of what

00:25:21.890 --> 00:25:23.764
it is that you're working with.

00:25:23.764 --> 00:25:25.430
So now when I work
with a guitar player,

00:25:25.430 --> 00:25:27.200
I have a much
deeper understanding

00:25:27.200 --> 00:25:30.247
of what it is that they're
doing besides me just

00:25:30.247 --> 00:25:32.080
asking for something
and them delivering it.

00:25:32.080 --> 00:25:33.500
I know what to ask for.

00:25:33.500 --> 00:25:35.930
I know what their first
physical limitations are.

00:25:35.930 --> 00:25:38.259
I know the limitations
of the instrument itself.

00:25:38.259 --> 00:25:40.550
I'm not going to sit here
and do a guitar solo for you,

00:25:40.550 --> 00:25:42.133
but I know enough
about the instrument

00:25:42.133 --> 00:25:44.870
to be able to work with
great guitar players

00:25:44.870 --> 00:25:48.430
and get more out of
that interaction.

00:25:48.430 --> 00:25:52.870
AUDIENCE: For me, I feel
like your fusion music was

00:25:52.870 --> 00:25:59.030
the first that connected
with me in a very

00:25:59.030 --> 00:26:01.100
pure and specific way.

00:26:01.100 --> 00:26:04.962
And yet, it's always
evolving and you're always

00:26:04.962 --> 00:26:06.170
pushing the boundaries on it.

00:26:06.170 --> 00:26:09.450
So where do you feel that
fusion music is today,

00:26:09.450 --> 00:26:11.580
and where do you
think it's headed?

00:26:11.580 --> 00:26:15.190
KARSH KALE: Well, I
think, fusion music

00:26:15.190 --> 00:26:17.660
has always been happening.

00:26:17.660 --> 00:26:18.950
That's what music is.

00:26:18.950 --> 00:26:22.080
I mean, everything, even Indian
classical music is fusion.

00:26:22.080 --> 00:26:24.320
It's a fusion of
many different ideas

00:26:24.320 --> 00:26:27.500
that come together on one stage.

00:26:27.500 --> 00:26:30.120
But these ideas come from
many different places.

00:26:30.120 --> 00:26:33.230
So I think that it's
always evolving.

00:26:33.230 --> 00:26:36.000
I mean, fusion is the process.

00:26:36.000 --> 00:26:37.460
It's not a style.

00:26:37.460 --> 00:26:40.430
It's not a particular
form of music.

00:26:40.430 --> 00:26:44.270
Fusion is the process that
we acknowledge as music

00:26:44.270 --> 00:26:46.130
is evolving in front of us.

00:26:46.130 --> 00:26:50.600
And we might have had a moment
where this was our time.

00:26:50.600 --> 00:26:53.870
This was the time where we
resonated most with that music.

00:26:53.870 --> 00:26:57.350
But it's-- I think that what I
see and what's happening today

00:26:57.350 --> 00:27:02.150
is another generation
of artists who are--

00:27:02.150 --> 00:27:04.990
they are already fused.

00:27:04.990 --> 00:27:08.960
They're growing up with U.
Srinivas and Zakir Hussain

00:27:08.960 --> 00:27:11.960
and John Coltrane and
the latest heavy metal

00:27:11.960 --> 00:27:14.280
album and the latest
Anderson Paak record

00:27:14.280 --> 00:27:16.610
and whatever new hip hop
record is coming out,

00:27:16.610 --> 00:27:18.230
all happening at the same time.

00:27:18.230 --> 00:27:20.744
And they're expressing
that all at the same time.

00:27:20.744 --> 00:27:22.160
I mean, some of
the artists that I

00:27:22.160 --> 00:27:25.040
work with now in my
collective in India

00:27:25.040 --> 00:27:28.169
are young artists who are
blowing my mind with how

00:27:28.169 --> 00:27:29.960
they're able to come
and be like, oh, yeah,

00:27:29.960 --> 00:27:31.700
it's this, this,
this, and that, right?

00:27:31.700 --> 00:27:34.300
So it's kind of
like a techno meets

00:27:34.300 --> 00:27:37.280
bhajan meets a light
classical thing

00:27:37.280 --> 00:27:43.250
with a little Carnatic twist,
and a dash of heavy metal.

00:27:43.250 --> 00:27:44.870
Whereas for us, it
took us years to be

00:27:44.870 --> 00:27:47.574
able to kind of get to that
point where we understood.

00:27:47.574 --> 00:27:49.490
So I think that, if
anything, that's, I think,

00:27:49.490 --> 00:27:50.281
where we're at now.

00:27:50.281 --> 00:27:53.810
It's that the music that we're
going to hear from now on

00:27:53.810 --> 00:27:56.977
is going to be on a
whole other level.

00:27:56.977 --> 00:27:57.810
AUDIENCE: Hi, Karsh.

00:27:57.810 --> 00:27:58.435
KARSH KALE: Hi.

00:27:58.435 --> 00:28:00.260
AUDIENCE: I'm a huge
fan of your work.

00:28:00.260 --> 00:28:01.990
I would like to
ask you about taste

00:28:01.990 --> 00:28:03.860
and if you, from
your own experience,

00:28:03.860 --> 00:28:07.670
have any ideas on creating a
rich journey of discovering

00:28:07.670 --> 00:28:08.720
new music?

00:28:08.720 --> 00:28:10.250
KARSH KALE: Well, I mean,
that was what I was actually

00:28:10.250 --> 00:28:11.060
addressing before.

00:28:11.060 --> 00:28:12.518
I think that there
is still-- there

00:28:12.518 --> 00:28:17.120
needs to be a little bit more
of a platform for new emerging

00:28:17.120 --> 00:28:20.660
artists who have
something new to say.

00:28:20.660 --> 00:28:23.690
Because oftentimes, it
gets lost in the mix.

00:28:23.690 --> 00:28:25.640
There's so much stuff
out there that it's

00:28:25.640 --> 00:28:28.109
hard to find the new stuff.

00:28:28.109 --> 00:28:29.900
And I think that that
also has to do with--

00:28:29.900 --> 00:28:35.690
it's also a curator's job to
bring those things together

00:28:35.690 --> 00:28:38.396
and present new music
in that particular way.

00:28:38.396 --> 00:28:40.520
And I think there are people
out there-- people who

00:28:40.520 --> 00:28:43.130
are doing podcasts and people
who are putting together

00:28:43.130 --> 00:28:45.890
playlists-- that a lot
of people check out

00:28:45.890 --> 00:28:48.320
because they trust what it is.

00:28:48.320 --> 00:28:50.900
I mean, I remember
when I was coming up,

00:28:50.900 --> 00:28:53.840
back then, it was
people's radio shows.

00:28:53.840 --> 00:28:55.760
But there were a
few people who were

00:28:55.760 --> 00:28:59.000
responsible for introducing
the world to some of the--

00:28:59.000 --> 00:29:02.240
I remember when my
second album had come out

00:29:02.240 --> 00:29:05.090
and Coldplay was
still a new band

00:29:05.090 --> 00:29:07.610
that was being
introduced as a brand

00:29:07.610 --> 00:29:10.661
new artist in this compilation
that I was a part of.

00:29:10.661 --> 00:29:12.410
Now they're, of course,
one of the biggest

00:29:12.410 --> 00:29:13.950
bands on the planet.

00:29:13.950 --> 00:29:17.370
But yeah, it was because there
was a platform like that.

00:29:17.370 --> 00:29:20.420
So I think that the important
thing is to be able to have,

00:29:20.420 --> 00:29:23.770
and encourage people, as
well, to share playlists

00:29:23.770 --> 00:29:27.500
and to share-- to curate--

00:29:27.500 --> 00:29:30.230
these kind of things
where people have access

00:29:30.230 --> 00:29:33.327
to new music and new artists.

00:29:33.327 --> 00:29:34.910
AUDIENCE: So one
thing I want to know,

00:29:34.910 --> 00:29:36.868
because you've been in
the industry for a while

00:29:36.868 --> 00:29:38.510
and you have worked
various artists

00:29:38.510 --> 00:29:40.800
from India or from elsewhere.

00:29:40.800 --> 00:29:42.110
How do they approach the music?

00:29:42.110 --> 00:29:44.068
I mean, what's the
difference in their approach

00:29:44.068 --> 00:29:45.570
to the music, which is--

00:29:45.570 --> 00:29:49.040
the Asian underground is still
based on Indian classical,

00:29:49.040 --> 00:29:49.890
to an extent.

00:29:49.890 --> 00:29:52.400
So how do they
approach the music

00:29:52.400 --> 00:29:54.734
based on their
cultural background?

00:29:54.734 --> 00:29:56.150
KARSH KALE: I mean,
I can't really

00:29:56.150 --> 00:29:59.060
say that there's a particular--

00:29:59.060 --> 00:30:02.390
I mean, every
musician is different.

00:30:02.390 --> 00:30:05.900
I've met artists that
are purists coming

00:30:05.900 --> 00:30:08.840
from the electronic music
world that don't really

00:30:08.840 --> 00:30:10.490
necessarily understand
how to step out

00:30:10.490 --> 00:30:12.080
of that particular box.

00:30:12.080 --> 00:30:13.640
I've met Indian
classical musicians

00:30:13.640 --> 00:30:15.530
who've been playing
for decades who

00:30:15.530 --> 00:30:20.210
have absolutely no issue
with hearing some grimy drum

00:30:20.210 --> 00:30:22.760
and bass track and know
exactly how it is that they

00:30:22.760 --> 00:30:24.104
fit into that context.

00:30:24.104 --> 00:30:25.520
So there's no real
answer to that.

00:30:25.520 --> 00:30:28.700
I mean, it really comes down
to the individual artists.

00:30:28.700 --> 00:30:30.680
I mean, there have been
classical musicians

00:30:30.680 --> 00:30:34.820
who I've worked with that
I've had to completely mute

00:30:34.820 --> 00:30:37.500
everything that I was working on
and just play a classical tabla

00:30:37.500 --> 00:30:40.640
part just so that they could
understand what the context was

00:30:40.640 --> 00:30:42.650
that I was trying
to bring them into.

00:30:42.650 --> 00:30:45.050
And usually, those are
actually younger artists.

00:30:45.050 --> 00:30:47.600
Older artists tend to
be a little bit more

00:30:47.600 --> 00:30:50.690
versatile because they've
been there and done that.

00:30:50.690 --> 00:30:53.120
We assume when we hear
musicians that this

00:30:53.120 --> 00:30:55.460
is what they do so this is
the bubble that they live in.

00:30:55.460 --> 00:30:57.640
But they hear everything.

00:30:57.640 --> 00:30:58.920
They've seen everything.

00:30:58.920 --> 00:31:00.060
And the older the artist--

00:31:00.060 --> 00:31:03.320
I mean, someone like Zakir
Bhai, who's not only seen,

00:31:03.320 --> 00:31:05.660
but he's lived
through, he's breathed

00:31:05.660 --> 00:31:08.390
through so many
different genres of music

00:31:08.390 --> 00:31:13.040
that his own audiences
still have no idea how much

00:31:13.040 --> 00:31:14.570
this guy has lived through.

00:31:14.570 --> 00:31:18.912
So when a guy like that
comes into the studio,

00:31:18.912 --> 00:31:20.870
I'm hard-pressed to throw
him a curveball where

00:31:20.870 --> 00:31:24.082
he's scratching his head.

00:31:24.082 --> 00:31:27.050
NIRDHAR KHAZANIE: Well, thanks
everyone for your questions.

00:31:27.050 --> 00:31:29.490
So we have a very nice surprise.

00:31:29.490 --> 00:31:31.160
It's that Karsh,
I think, is going

00:31:31.160 --> 00:31:35.600
to give us a quick little
demonstration of the tabla.

00:31:35.600 --> 00:31:40.270
KARSH KALE: So for those of you
who have not seen these drums,

00:31:40.270 --> 00:31:41.186
it's called the tabla.

00:31:44.378 --> 00:31:47.420
Traditionally, an Indian
classical instrument,

00:31:47.420 --> 00:31:50.810
but now used all
over the world in all

00:31:50.810 --> 00:31:54.260
walks of music, whether it be
in Hollywood films or hip hop

00:31:54.260 --> 00:31:58.370
music or pop music or Kirtan--

00:31:58.370 --> 00:32:00.530
all kinds of stuff.

00:32:00.530 --> 00:32:02.660
And it's also an incredibly
versatile instrument

00:32:02.660 --> 00:32:05.180
in that it's not only
a rhythm instrument,

00:32:05.180 --> 00:32:08.780
it's also a tonal instrument,
a melodic instrument.

00:32:08.780 --> 00:32:11.420
And it's a a talking
drum, as well.

00:32:11.420 --> 00:32:12.050
It can speak.

00:32:12.050 --> 00:32:13.980
It can have conversations.

00:32:13.980 --> 00:32:15.110
So the way that--

00:32:15.110 --> 00:32:19.370
the repertoire that we
learn is based on syllables.

00:32:19.370 --> 00:32:21.710
These are syllables
that we turn into words.

00:32:21.710 --> 00:32:23.960
Then these words, we
turn into paragraphs,

00:32:23.960 --> 00:32:27.370
and we create stories.

00:32:27.370 --> 00:32:30.860
There is a particular
rhythm called Keherwa,

00:32:30.860 --> 00:32:34.640
which is probably one of
the most popular rhythms

00:32:34.640 --> 00:32:36.070
all over the planet.

00:32:36.070 --> 00:32:38.090
And you hear it in
devotional music.

00:32:38.090 --> 00:32:39.599
You hear it in Bhangra.

00:32:39.599 --> 00:32:40.640
You hear it in Bollywood.

00:32:40.640 --> 00:32:42.437
You hear it in reggae music.

00:32:42.437 --> 00:32:44.270
You hear it in all kinds
of different music.

00:32:44.270 --> 00:32:49.670
And it's a very simple rhythm
that anyone can learn, and then

00:32:49.670 --> 00:32:50.420
expand upon.

00:32:54.890 --> 00:32:57.819
So the syllables
of Keherwa are--

00:32:57.819 --> 00:32:58.360
[DRUM SOUNDS]

00:32:58.360 --> 00:33:00.950
dhin, naa.

00:33:00.950 --> 00:33:03.839
So it's dhin naa,
dhin, dhin naa.

00:33:03.839 --> 00:33:05.320
Dhin naa, dhin, dhin naa.

00:33:05.320 --> 00:33:06.242
So dhin--

00:33:06.242 --> 00:33:09.008
[DRUM SOUNDS]

00:33:09.930 --> 00:33:17.620
So that's the general
composition of Keherwa.

00:33:17.620 --> 00:33:20.540
But there's many, many different
interpretations of that.

00:33:20.540 --> 00:33:22.790
So I'll kind of take you
through a little bit of that.

00:33:22.790 --> 00:33:25.778
[TABLA MUSIC]

00:34:37.490 --> 00:34:40.478
[APPLAUSE]

00:34:41.911 --> 00:34:43.785
It was kind of like
typing with a typewriter.

00:34:43.785 --> 00:34:45.679
I had to keep moving it back.

00:34:45.679 --> 00:34:47.347
But thank you.

00:34:47.347 --> 00:34:48.930
